<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911105-0082</DOCNO><DOCID>911105-0082.</DOCID><HL>   GM's Hughes Aircraft   Gets $300 Million Pact   To Build 3 Satellites</HL><DATE>11/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5</SO><CO>   GM GMH</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)AUTOMOBILES (AUT)</IN><RE>ARABIAN PENINSULA (ARA)CALIFORNIA (CA)CANADA (CN)CONNECTICUT (CT)MICHIGAN (MI)MIDDLE EAST (ML)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)SAUDI ARABIA (SA)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- Hughes Aircraft Co. said its Space andCommunications Group signed a $300 million contract to buildthree communications satellites for Alpha Lyracom.   The satellites, Hughes's HS 601 models, will be used forinternational telecommunications. Alpha Lyracom, based inGreenwich, Conn., is a private global communicationssatellite operator. Hughes is a unit of General Motors Corp.</LP><TEXT>   The first satellite, called ORBX 2, is slated for launchin May 1994 and will serve the Pacific Ocean region. Theremaining satellites, ORBX 3 and 4, are scheduled for launchduring the third and fourth quarters of 1994 and will provideservice in the Atlantic and Indian Ocean regions,respectively. Each satellite is designed for a lifetime of 15years, Hughes said.   Separately, Hughes said it formed a new subsidiary, HughesSaudi Arabia Ltd., to develop &quot;in-country businessopportunities in the fields of satellite-basedcommunications, software and systems engineering andelectro-optical depot operations.&quot; Earlier this year, Hugheswas selected to build a $837 million command, control andcommunications system for Saudi Arabia.</TEXT></DOC>